Title : Walter Shirley, 11th Earl Ferrers
Text : '''Walter Knight Shirley, 11th Earl Ferrers''' (5 June 1864 – 2 February 1937) was a British architect and nobleman.

Born at [[Christ Church, Oxford]], where his father was a professor and canon, Shirley was the second but only surviving son of Rev. [[Walter Waddington Shirley]] (d. 1866) and his wife Philippa Knight.<ref name="visitation">{{cite book | editor=Frederick Arthur Crisp | title=Visitation of England and Wales | volume=12 | year=1904 | page=90 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xScwAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA90}}</ref>

Educated at [[Winchester College]] and [[New College, Oxford]], whence he took a B.A. in 1887,<ref name="visitation" /> Shirley entered the profession of architecture and was [[Articled clerk|articled]] to [[Basil Champneys]].<ref name="obit">{{cite journal | title=Obituaries | journal=Journal of the Royal Institute of British Architects | year=1937 | volume=44 | page=414}}</ref> Part of the [[Arts and Crafts Movement]], he was an active member of the [[Society for the Protection of Ancient Buildings]] and the [[Art Workers Guild]]. He designed a large addition to 35 [[Victoria Road, Kensington|Victoria Road]], [[Kensington]] in 1896.<ref>{{cite book | title=Southern Kensington: Kensington Square to Earls Court | author=Greater London Council | publisher=Athlone Press | year=1986 | page=148}}</ref><ref>{{cite book | title=London 3: North West | first1=Bridget | last1=Cherry | first2=Nikolaus | last2=Pevsner | authorlink2=Nikolaus Pevsner | publisher=Yale University Press | year=1991 | page=515}}</ref> Shirley's obituary described him as "a most conscientious architect...over-exacting, if anything, in his own work".<ref name="obit" />

On 9 July 1890, Shirley married Mary Jane Moon (d. 10 Jan 1944), daughter of the barrister Robert Moon and the sister of [[Edward Robert Pacy Moon]], by whom he had five children:<ref name="visitation" />
*Lady Margery Joan Shirley (25 November 1891 – 1 June 1952), married Lancelot Sackville Fletcher on 22 September 1920
*Elizabeth Mary Shirley (30 December 1892 – 9 November 1893)
*[[Robert Shirley, 12th Earl Ferrers]] (1894–1954)
*Lady Phillida Shirley (4 November 1896 – 26 December 1985), under the name of Sister Mary Phillida a [[recluse]] at the Anglican shrine to [[Our Lady of Walsingham]]
*Hon. Andrew Shirley (29 December 1900 – 20 June 1958), married Ethel Muriel Lewis on 30 April 1927 and had issue, art historian

In 1912, Shirley succeeded his childless fourth cousin as [[Earl Ferrers]], and largely retired from architecture to tend the family estates. He died at the family seat of [[Staunton Harold Hall]] in 1937.<ref name="obit" />

